The study also found inconclusive evidence to suggest that traditional gender roles may contribute to Nigerian men’s negative attitudes toward abortion.

An estimated 131 countries have abortion laws that are more restrictive than Nigeria’s, including in sub-Saharan Africa.

“A subset of these are countries in which the overall rates of abortion are the same or higher than in Nigeria, despite being more liberalized in the eyes of the law,” the study’s authors said.

According to the report, Australia, Finland, India, the Netherlands and Belgium are the only five countries with consistently high or relatively high fertility alongside abortion rates higher than Nigeria’s.

Kenya, Uganda, Tanzania and Ethiopia, alongside Nigeria, were among the 103 countries with the most restrictive laws and highest abortion rates.

Countries with “low would-be-pregnancy rates but still with highly restrictive abortion laws, while having both relatively liberalized marriage rates and higher proportions of women in the labor force have lower abortion rates (than Nigeria),” according to the study.
